The paper deals with the scheduling design of a mobile-edge computing (MEC) system, which involves the optimization of task offloading decision, uplink transmission device selection, and power allocation. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) category, which deals with the design, implementation, and evaluation of networked systems. Additionally, the paper involves the use of Markov decision processes (MDPs) to formulate the optimization problem, which suggests that it could also belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) category, which deals with the design and analysis of distributed systems. The paper also deals with uncertainty in device number and location, which suggests that it could belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) category, which deals with the modeling, analysis, and control of complex systems. Furthermore, the paper involves the use of optimization techniques, which suggests that it could belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) category, which deals with the study of information processing and communication. Finally, the paper proposes a low-complexity sub-optimal solution framework, which suggests that it could also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) category, which deals with the study of intelligent agents and their behavior.
